# Fluff Date: 2026-02-26 19:50:04
<overview>
<p>The Tyre is a medium-weight aerospace fighter developed by Clan Steel Viper in 2907, conceived as a homegrown successor to the Corsair class fighter that had nearly vanished among the Clans' ancestors during the long journey from the Inner Sphere. After years of iterative development and numerous proposed enhancements, Viper designers settled on a design that deliberately traded maximum speed for resilience and concentrated firepower, producing a craft ideally suited to the DropShip escort role the Clan urgently needed to fill. Economical to operate and straightforward to maintain by Clan standards, the Tyre found a ready home not only in Steel Viper aerospace forces but across much of the Clan homeworld complex. While newer OmniFighters eventually displaced it from front-line duty among wealthier Clans, the Tyre remained a fixture of second-line forces throughout the Clan universe, valued for dependability and sustained combat effectiveness against both aerospace and ground targets.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>Built around economy and durability rather than raw performance, the Tyre mounts a standard fusion powerplant that limits it to a top acceleration of four Gs, average by the standards of heavier craft but deliberately matched to the pace of the DropShips it was designed to escort. The design philosophy treats this modest speed as a feature, keeping the fighter close to its assigned convoy rather than being lured away by enemy interceptors seeking to draw off the screen.</p><p>Seven and a half tons of Formula TSF Standard armor protects the airframe, with additional mass concentrated in the nose and forward fuselage to survive frontal engagement. The primary armament pairs a Type 9-A Ultra autocannon with seven Series AP7 medium pulse lasers, a combination that emphasizes concentrated close-range firepower over standoff reach. All weapons may be fired simultaneously without overtaxing the heat sinks, making the Tyre an exceptionally reliable strafing platform against surface targets and an unforgiving opponent at close quarters.</p><p>The trade-off is a significant lack of reach, and opposing fighters who maintain their distance hold a clear tactical advantage. Heat dissipation is matched tightly to the weapons load with little surplus, leaving pilots minimal margin during extended engagements. Both weaknesses are well-understood among Clan aerospace pilots, and the Tyre's tactical reputation reflects a design that punishes the enemy hardest when it can close the range.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The base Tyre served as the standard aerospace escort in Steel Viper DropShip formations and spread to all Clans through Trials and trade during the homeworld period. Produced at multiple Clan facilities, it became the most common aerospace fighter type in second-line formations across the Clan homeworlds by the late Golden Century. Clans historically underserved in OmniFighters, including the Blood Spirits and Cloud Cobras, routinely employed Tyres in front-line roles to compensate for gaps in their premier combat assets.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>The Tyre traces its lineage back to the Corsair, the capable medium fighter that served as a backbone of Star League aerospace forces before Operation Exodus. The Corsair had seen heavy attrition during the liberation of Terra and the years of conflict that followed, and by the time Kerensky's forces departed the Inner Sphere the design was already declining in availability. The journey across the void further reduced their numbers, and when the Clans were formed from the survivors of the Exodus fleet, functioning Corsairs had become scarce, leaving the warrior caste dependent on whatever craft had survived the long passage.</p><p>Clan Steel Viper aerospace engineers undertook a deliberate program to fill this gap, studying the Corsair's operational strengths and the particular demands of the nascent Clan military. Numerous design proposals were advanced, tested, and revised over the course of several years. Performance characteristics were adjusted, weapons configurations evaluated, and structural details refined through the iterative process common to early Clan engineering efforts. Viper designers finally declared success in 2907, fielding what they named the Tyre. The new fighter quickly became the foundation of the Clan's aerospace fleet, serving primarily as the premier escort for DropShips moving through potentially hostile space.</p><p>Through the Trials and trading that shaped Clan interactions during the homeworld period, the Tyre spread widely among the other Clans. Production facilities were established on New Kent, Albion, Bearclaw, Babylon, Homer, Roche, and York, giving nearly every Clan access to domestically produced examples at various points during the early centuries. As OmniFighters were developed and proliferated among the wealthier Clans during the later Golden Century and into the Clan Invasion era, the Tyre was progressively shifted to second-line assignments. Clans historically short on resources for OmniFighters continued using Tyres in front-line roles, and all Clans maintained some quantity in their reserve aerospace forces.</p><p>The Steel Vipers maintained the most concentrated production at their New Kent orbital facility, which became the definitive source of later production runs as other homeworld facilities scaled back or ceased operations. The Vipers' eventual Annihilation following the Wars of Reaving brought New Kent production to an end, but the design found an unexpected second life in the Inner Sphere when Janesek Industries on Orestes began producing modified variants under Ghost Bear occupation during the Dark Age, later continuing under Republic Dominion sponsorship and extending the Tyre's service well into the ilClan era.</p>
</history>

